      Anti-ESG
   =20
 =20

My basic view of bubbles is that if you can identify a bubble, and you have=
 some free time, the right move is to sell into the bubble. Not sell=C2=A0s=
hort, mind you, which is risky; you don=E2=80=99t know when the bubble will=
=C2=A0pop. Sell long. Get into the business that is bubbly, because that=E2=
=80=99s where the money is. There is demand; become the supply. My  model o=
f Adam Neumann is that he correctly identified a huge bubble in venture fun=
ding for fast-growing not-quite-tech companies, positioned himself in front=
 of a=C2=A0firehose of SoftBank money, and became dynastically wealthy as t=
hat bubble popped. He was the Big Short of the recent tech bubble, but with=
out the timing risk of actually selling short.
Or in=C2=A02017 every random micro-cap public company  pivoted to the block=
chain. Correctly!
  [1]

Similarly with the=C2=A0rise of environmental, social and governance invest=
ing over the last few years. As an=C2=A0investor, you might have views like=
 =E2=80=9CESG is a fad and I will short stocks that are popular with ESG fu=
nds, betting that their valuations will collapse,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CESG =
is a rising trend and I will get long stocks that have good ESG scores, bet=
ting that there will be continued demand for them,=E2=80=9D
  [2]
=C2=A0and these are hard calls to make and require timing. But if you were =
just, like, looking around for something to do, surely starting an investme=
nt fund or consultancy or ratings firm or whatever and saying =E2=80=9Cwe w=
ill be very very ESG indeed=E2=80=9D was a good=C2=A0marketing strategy. Sl=
apping an =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D label on things allowed you to charge high =
fees and raise a lot of money, and people did.
But in recent months there has been a=C2=A0vogue for=C2=A0anti-ESG, and wha=
tever you think of its merits it is just an obviously lucrative market to s=
ell into.=C2=A0Right now, if you go around saying =E2=80=9CI am going to do=
 a financial business, but I will make a point of not considering environme=
ntal, social or governance factors,=E2=80=9D or even =E2=80=9CI will consid=
er ESG=C2=A0factors, but only to do the opposite=C2=A0of what those =E2=80=
=98woke=E2=80=99 ESG funds do,=E2=80=9D people will fling money at you. You=
 can walk into Peter Thiel=E2=80=99s office wearing a clown suit and say =
=E2=80=9Chigh-frequency trading, but anti-woke,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cpayday=
 lending, but anti-woke,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cvariable annuities, but anti-=
woke,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Ccapped/uncapped variance swaps, but anti-woke,=
=E2=80=9D or whatever, and he will write you a big check. =E2=80=9C_____ bu=
t not ESG=E2=80=9D is a business model that can raise money right now, so w=
hy aren=E2=80=99t you doing it?
One subtle advantage of this business model is that a way to signal that yo=
u are authentically anti-ESG is by having bad governance, since =E2=80=9Cgo=
vernance=E2=80=9D is right there in the name of the thing you (and your inv=
estors)=C2=A0are against. This can work to your advantage: Bad governance t=
ends to be bad for investors but good for entrepreneurs. (Ask   Adam Neuman=
n!)=C2=A0You raise a bunch of money and then spend it on yachts for yoursel=
f, and your investors=C2=A0say things like =E2=80=9Cwell the governance of =
this company is pretty bad isn=E2=80=99t it,=E2=80=9D and you=C2=A0say =E2=
=80=9Cexactly!=E2=80=9D Bad governance is what they signed up for!
Here is a Wall Street Journal article about an =E2=80=9Canti-woke bank=E2=
=80=9D that just reads all the way through like a parody, which is how you =
know it=E2=80=99s a good idea:

The startup, called GloriFi, initially aimed to launch with bank accounts, =
credit cards, mortgages and insurance, while touting what it called pro-Ame=
rica values such as capitalism, family, law enforcement and the freedom to =
=E2=80=9Ccelebrate your love of God and country.=E2=80=9D
Within months, the investors=E2=80=99 money was nearly gone, and GloriFi wa=
s on the verge of bankruptcy. It missed launch dates, blaming faulty techno=
logy and failures by vendors, and laid off dozens of employees. It stumbled=
 with products; for instance, a plan to make a credit card out of the same =
material used for shell casings failed when the company realized the materi=
al could interfere with security chips and potentially be too thick for pay=
ment terminals, according to people familiar with the matter.

Sure! Look, you can=E2=80=99t actually make credit cards out of bullets, bu=
t in 2022 you can raise infinity dollars=C2=A0by walking into the right roo=
m and=C2=A0saying the words =E2=80=9Cmake credit cards out of bullets.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0That=C2=A0is the financial innovation here.
GloriFi=E2=80=99s founder, Toby Neugebauer,=C2=A0is =E2=80=9Cthe son of a f=
ormer Texas congressman=E2=80=9D and an oil-and-gas investor. And there=E2=
=80=99s this:
Of the criticism of his alleged drinking, he said, =E2=80=9CThe attacks on =
what I do in my home after 5 p.m. are beneath=E2=80=9D The Wall Street Jour=
nal. =E2=80=A6
Which I would say is generally a fair point, except that his home was also =
the headquarters of the company, and what=C2=A0he=C2=A0allegedly does in hi=
s home after 5 p.m. is drink and berate the employees who work there:

Mr. Neugebauer=E2=80=99s 16,000-square-foot Dallas home, modeled after the =
White House, became the company=E2=80=99s initial headquarters.=C2=A0=E2=80=
=A6
But staffers began complaining about what they said were Mr. Neugebauer=E2=
=80=99s volatile behavior and drinking habits, according to people familiar=
 with the matter and a memo from Britt Amos, GloriFi=E2=80=99s former head =
of human resources, reviewed by the Journal. Ms. Amos left in the spring af=
ter clashing with Mr. Neugebauer, and she recounted issues she saw as probl=
ems in the memo.
=E2=80=9CSeveral people working at the mansion told me to make sure I leave=
 around six,=E2=80=9D Ms. Amos wrote in the memo. =E2=80=9CWhen I inquired =
why, they stated that after 5 p.m. Toby starts drinking and things at the h=
ouse deteriorate quickly.=E2=80=9D

Presumably this scores very low on the=C2=A0governance part of ESG checklis=
ts, which is what they=E2=80=99re going for. Another anti-ESG entrepreneur,=
 Vivek Ramaswamy, also makes an appearance:

Around this time, one of GloriFi=E2=80=99s investors, Vivek Ramaswamy, was =
working to launch his own financial-services firm. Strive Asset Management =
would offer investors an alternative to firms such as BlackRock Inc., which=
 has pushed companies to improve diversity and cut their climate emissions,=
 among other changes. Strive, instead, would push companies to focus on mak=
ing money, not taking stands on social or political issues.
Mr. Neugebauer said he was furious and was convinced that Mr. Ramaswamy, wh=
o wrote the book =E2=80=9CWoke, Inc.,=E2=80=9D had stolen his idea. Mr. Neu=
gebauer said he had even invested in Strive, thinking it was a conservative=
 beer startup.

Asset management! Beer! It doesn=E2=80=99t matter! The product is not the p=
oint.

