      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20

Here=E2=80=99s another way=C2=A0that Elon Musk=E2=80=99s deal to buy Twitte=
r Inc. could have gone:

In recent weeks, Mr. Musk proposed buying Twitter at a discount of as much =
as 30 percent. Discussions later narrowed to around 10 percent, people fami=
liar with those conversations said.
Twitter appeared willing to negotiate on the price, said Alex Spiro, a lawy=
er representing Mr. Musk.
=E2=80=9CTwitter offered Mr. Musk billions off the transaction price. Mr. M=
usk refused because Twitter attempted to put certain self-serving condition=
s on the deal,=E2=80=9D Mr. Spiro said, without adding more details. A Twit=
ter spokesman declined to respond to a request for comment on the claim.
On Monday, after those conversations had fizzled, Mr. Musk informed the com=
pany that he was ready to proceed with the original price he offered in Apr=
il.

What were those =E2=80=9Cself-serving conditions=E2=80=9D? It seems like on=
e of them might have been something to the effect of =E2=80=9Cbut you actua=
lly have to pay,=E2=80=9D like:

Twitter: Okay we=E2=80=99ll do $50 per share, but you have to promise not t=
o come to us tomorrow with some new insane excuse for why you won=E2=80=99t=
 close.
Musk: No deal!

This sort of condition would be=C2=A0pretty standard. We   have talked abou=
t Thoma Bravo=E2=80=99s deal for Anaplan Inc., for instance. Thoma Bravo sh=
amelessly retraded on the agreed price, and Anaplan gave it a 3.4% price cu=
t, but in exchange Thoma Bravo essentially waived all of its=C2=A0condition=
s, requirements, etc., and agreed to close no matter what.=C2=A0I suggested=
 this as a possible model for Twitter and Musk repricing their deal, but ap=
parently it didn=E2=80=99t work.
Another =E2=80=9Cself-serving condition=E2=80=9D might have been something =
to the effect of =E2=80=9Cokay, we=E2=80=99ll give you a price cut, but whe=
n shareholders sue us personally, you=E2=80=99ll defend us and pay any judg=
ment.=E2=80=9D It=C2=A0would=C2=A0have been kind of self-serving for Twitte=
r=E2=80=99s directors to give Musk a price cut (which comes out of the pock=
ets of their shareholders) in exchange for reducing their=C2=A0risk of=C2=
=A0personal=C2=A0liability. Also it might not have worked out to be a price=
 cut, really:
=09Twitter=E2=80=99s directors cut the price from $54.20 to $50; the deal c=
loses.=09Shareholders sue, saying =E2=80=9Cyou had a good deal at $54.20, i=
t was ironclad, and you disloyally gave some of that back to Musk=C2=A0for =
your own personal convenience.=E2=80=9D=09This is correct, and they win a j=
udgment of $4.20 per share, plus interest.=09Musk pays it.=09Might as well =
have just paid $54.20 in the first place, no?

If that was the sticking point, you can see why Musk would say no. A   poss=
ibly related point from Bloomberg News last week:
Musk is also seeking to reserve his rights to file a fraud suit over his cl=
aims the platform=E2=80=99s executives misled him and other investors about=
 the number of spam and robot accounts among its more than 230 million user=
s, according to one of the people, who asked not to be named discussing non=
-public matters.
Well, look, it=C2=A0is=C2=A0a weird feature of US securities law that share=
holders regularly sue companies for misleading them, and those companies re=
gularly settle those lawsuits, and the companies pay money to the sharehold=
ers, but the money=C2=A0comes from the shareholders. The money belongs to t=
he shareholders, so paying it out as damages seems counterproductive. I sup=
pose there are some differences. (If you owned shares at the time of the fr=
aud, and you don=E2=80=99t now, you get some money at the expense of the cu=
rrent shareholders. Plus insurers probably pay some of it.) Still it is goi=
ng to be very funny if Musk ends up buying Twitter, sues it for misleading =
him into buying it, wins=C2=A0and pays himself damages.=C2=A0
What else. There is Musk=E2=80=99s financing. Some $13 billion of the $46-i=
sh billion that he needs to buy Twitter will come from his banks; it seems =
likely that they will unhappily fund these loans, though there is still som=
e possibility of drama there, and if they don=E2=80=99t fund then he may be=
 able to get out of the deal. Musk is on the hook for the remaining $33 bil=
lion, but back in happier times he found equity co-investors to buy about $=
7 billion of that. If they back out, (1) he has to cover that $7 billion an=
d (2) I guess he could sue them? That would be weird.=C2=A0They=E2=80=99re =
not going to back out, though: They invested pretty whimsically, on the str=
ength of   a quick text message and the thesis =E2=80=9CElon Musk is good a=
t business and Twitter is important, broken and probably fixable,=E2=80=9D =
and/or =E2=80=9CElon Musk is really rich and kicking a few hundred million =
dollars into his latest lark will probably pay off for us somehow.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0Since then interest rates are up, the market is down, Twitter=E2=80=
=99s business is hurting, etc., but those theses are mostly=C2=A0unchanged.=
  So:

At least two major equity investors backing Elon Musk=E2=80=99s deal to buy=
 Twitter plan to go ahead with their=C2=A0funding, as the billionaire moves=
 toward closing the deal after dramatically reversing his position on it.
Sequoia Capital, which has committed $800 million to the deal, plans to kee=
p its funding in place, according to a person familiar with the matter. Mea=
nwhile, a spokesperson for cryptocurrency exchange Binance, which is slated=
 to contribute $500 million to the deal, told The Information that its comm=
itment hasn=E2=80=99t changed.

That leaves him writing about a $26 billion check, and it is not entirely c=
lear to me if he has that much money in cash.=C2=A0Tesla Inc. is  scheduled=
 to announce earnings on Oct. 19, which presumably will open a window for M=
usk to sell more Tesla stock if he needs to to raise the rest of the money.
While he waits to close, Musk is doing things like  calling on China to ann=
ex Taiwan=C2=A0and asking Kanye West not to tweet about =E2=80=9Cgoing deat=
h con 3 on Jewish people,=E2=80=9D so the new golden age of free speech on =
Twitter is gonna be weird.=C2=A0

