   =20
      Margin call
   =20
 =20

One thing that banks do is make margin loans. You lend money to people, sec=
ured by their stock in a publicly traded company. You lend, say, 20% to 50%=
 of the value of the stock, and if the stock drops you can demand that they=
 put up more collateral or repay some of the loan. The risk to you is mostl=
y that the stock falls too fast: You lend $40 against $100 worth of stock, =
and the stock falls to $60 and you send an email demanding more collateral,=
 and by the time the borrower replies to the email the stock is at $20 and =
you=E2=80=99re not getting your money back.
One particularly interesting class of margin borrowers are the chief execut=
ive officers, board members and senior executives=C2=A0of public companies =
who want to borrow against their own companies=E2=80=99 stock. In a sense, =
CEOs are the most obvious margin borrowers: If=C2=A0I=C2=A0own publicly tra=
ded stock and want money, I can just sell the stock, but it is more awkward=
 for a CEO to sell her own company=E2=80=99s stock. Selling stock might red=
uce her control of the company, and it will generally=C2=A0look bad=C2=A0an=
d upset shareholders, so she might be inclined to get money by borrowing ag=
ainst her stock instead of selling it.=C2=A0
But CEOs are particularly risky margin borrowers. For instance, one risk of=
 making a margin loan to a public company CEO is that if the stock drops yo=
u might have to=C2=A0force him to quit his job, which will probably make th=
e stock drop more:

John Foley, the co-founder and former chief executive of Peloton Interactiv=
e Inc., faced repeated margin calls on money he borrowed against his Peloto=
n holdings before he left the fitness company=E2=80=99s board last month, a=
ccording to people familiar with the situation.
As Peloton=E2=80=99s shares slumped over the past year, Goldman Sachs Group=
 Inc. asked Mr. Foley several times to provide fresh funds or additional co=
llateral for personal loans the bank had extended to him, the people said. =
The company=E2=80=99s share price has fallen nearly 95% from its $160 peak =
in December 2020.
Resigning from the board gave Mr. Foley flexibility to sell or pledge more =
Peloton shares, though he said the margin calls weren=E2=80=99t the reason =
he left the company. =E2=80=A6
His seat on the board limited his ability to raise additional funds because=
 most public companies prohibit directors and executives from selling their=
 shares during certain trading periods. In addition, Peloton=E2=80=99s poli=
cy limits pledges for margin loans by directors or executives to 40% of the=
 value of an individual=E2=80=99s shares or vested options. ...
=E2=80=9CEveryone can see I had a rocky year,=E2=80=9D Mr. Foley said. =E2=
=80=9CThis was not a fun personal balance-sheet reset.=E2=80=9D

To be clear, Foley   stepped down=C2=A0as CEO=C2=A0in February, and the sto=
ck rallied briefly; his departure from the board in September doesn=E2=80=
=99t seem to have done all that much to the stock price. But in general if =
you are a founder, board member and executive chairman of a company, and yo=
u find yourself leaving the company so that you can spend more time=C2=A0wi=
th the money you borrowed against=C2=A0your stock, something has gone a bit=
 wrong.

