      Nobel Prize
   =20
 =20

The  cool  people on economics Twitter were going around yesterday saying, =
like, =E2=80=9Ceveryone knew about bank runs=C2=A0way=C2=A0before Diamond a=
nd Dybvig popularized them,=E2=80=9D and I guess that is fair; certainly I =
saw =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a Wonderful Life=E2=80=9D before I read =E2=80=9C=
Bank Runs, Deposit Insurance, and Liquidity.=E2=80=9D Still if you asked me=
 what has been the most important economic concept of my career, perhaps of=
 my adult life, I guess I=E2=80=99d say =E2=80=9Cbank runs=E2=80=9D? The 20=
08 global financial crisis was a sort of generalized bank run, run dynamics=
 are at the heart of  a lot of=C2=A0problems since then, and crypto has inv=
ented  exciting new ways to have bank runs. So awarding  the Nobel Memorial=
 Prize in Economics to Ben Bernanke, Douglas Diamond and Philip Dybvig for =
their work on =E2=80=9Cwhy banks are needed, why they are vulnerable and wh=
at to do about it=E2=80=9D seems pretty reasonable.

