<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing that banks do is make margin loans. =
You lend money to people, secured by their stock in a publicly traded compa=
ny. You lend, say, 20% to 50% of the value of the stock, and if the stock d=
rops you can demand that they put up more collateral or repay some of the l=
oan. The risk to you is mostly that the stock falls too fast: You lend $40 =
against $100 worth of stock, and the stock falls to $60 and you send an ema=
il demanding more collateral, and by the time the borrower replies to the e=
mail the stock is at $20 and you=E2=80=99re not getting your money back.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One particularly interesting class of margin b=
orrowers are the chief executive officers, board members and senior executi=
ves=C2=A0of public companies who want to borrow against their own companies=
=E2=80=99 stock. In a sense, CEOs are the most obvious margin borrowers: If=
=C2=A0<em>I=C2=A0</em>own publicly traded stock and want money, I can just =
sell the stock, but it is more awkward for a CEO to sell her own company=E2=
=80=99s stock. Selling stock might reduce her control of the company, and i=
t will generally=C2=A0<em>look bad=C2=A0</em>and upset shareholders, so she=
 might be inclined to get money by borrowing against her stock instead of s=
elling it.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But CEOs are particularly risky margin borrowe=
rs. For instance, one risk of making a margin loan to a public company CEO =
is that if the stock drops you might have to=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29339418.286265/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9=
hcnRpY2xlcy9wZWxvdG9uLWNvLWZvdW5kZXItam9obi1mb2xleS1mYWNlZC1yZXBlYXRlZC1tYX=
JnaW4tY2FsbHMtZnJvbS1nb2xkbWFuLXNhY2hzLWFzLXN0b2NrLXNsdW1wZWQtMTE2NjU0ODg5M=
Dg_bW9kPWhwX2xlYWRfcG9zNQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2f99d60d" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"><em>fo=
rce him to quit his job</em></a>, which will probably make the stock drop m=
ore:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">John Foley, the co-founder and former chief ex=
ecutive of Peloton Interactive Inc., faced repeated margin calls on money h=
e borrowed against his Peloton holdings before he left the fitness company=
=E2=80=99s board last month, according to people familiar with the situatio=
n.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As Peloton=E2=80=99s shares slumped over the p=
ast year, Goldman Sachs Group Inc. asked Mr. Foley several times to provide=
 fresh funds or additional collateral for personal loans the bank had exten=
ded to him, the people said. The company=E2=80=99s share price has fallen n=
early 95% from its $160 peak in December 2020.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Resigning from the board gave Mr. Foley flexib=
ility to sell or pledge more Peloton shares, though he said the margin call=
s weren=E2=80=99t the reason he left the company. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">His seat on the board limited his ability to r=
aise additional funds because most public companies prohibit directors and =
executives from selling their shares during certain trading periods. In add=
ition, Peloton=E2=80=99s policy limits pledges for margin loans by director=
s or executives to 40% of the value of an individual=E2=80=99s shares or ve=
sted options. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CEveryone can see I had a rocky year,=
=E2=80=9D Mr. Foley said. =E2=80=9CThis was not a fun personal balance-shee=
t reset.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
